cujoo wrote: Politically I hate Ayngaran International... They are anti- tamil people. During the sunami disaster period they gave money to Sinhalese Government , not Tamil organizations who were helping in Northern Srilanaka . They are BASTARDS!!!!!!!.

But I have to watch da movie for AJITH.....

To assume that people care about Aryan/Dravidian divide, etc is being judgmental. People have lot more important things to do. First, being a "Thamizh" is by nature of luck, (born thamizhians) or choice (for eg, naturalized thamizhians). Let's not romanticize this. Thamizh is just another language like English, French, Urdu or Hindi. One could be fanatical about the cultural, linguistic, and various other ethnical significance. But nevertheless, that shall be personal, and not to chuck it down the throats. One could very well enlighten, and spell it out for the coming generations, but let's not step over the line. Moreover, there's a judgmentality exhibited by few people. On the other side, At risk of sounding judgmental myself, there are also faux-hippies who try to be a wannabe, um, you know the pseudos act "hip" by exhibiting English and Indhi. Tamilians trying to be "Indhi" on pretense of being uber-cool, and who would nod their head for anything non-Tamil. Some who believe tamil sounds more "regressive", and what nots. Such misconceptions are not a sin as such, but it's something that reeks of a harsh commentary and rebuttal. With the l interaction I have had with my NI colleagues and friends - I have learnt how aggressive they are when it comes to their own 'Indhi' and I have blunty told them that they deserve the treatment they get from the SIs - specially from the Thamizhians.

Months ago at the Delhi airport when I was responded in Hindi for the questions asked in English - and when I replied back saying that I dont understand Hindi the response I got was "we dont understand English either" . I have not seen that kind of arrogance in TN or any where (and i made the fellows almost fall on my feet, when I asked them to provide me a feedback form - so that I can request the management to have somebody who knows English at the counter to attend to 'non hindhi' passengers like me) Whys Shriya seeking help?

Shriya Saran is trying to make a mark in Bollywood and is working hard to polish her skills. We heard that she did much to get theatre personality Barry John to give her private tuitions in acting. But Barry believes in teaching in groups only. So instead, the girl sent to him her film DVDs and sought his feedback and opinion. Well, we hear that Barry did manage to see a few of her flicks, and even commented that the girl will get better with time  just like wine, huh? But Shriya is on top of the world, and is happy to get guidance from Barry Looks like Shriya doesnt mind seeking help to be successful.
